---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import '../../../styles/global.css';
export const prerender = true;
---

<Layout title="How Much Does a Custom Website Cost in the UK? (2026 Pricing Guide) | xSoft Blog" description="Transparent UK website pricing for 2026. From brochure sites to enterprise platforms — what you'll actually pay, what's included, and how to avoid hidden costs." keywords="website cost UK, custom website price, web development pricing 2026, UK web agency cost, website quote UK, bespoke website cost">

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "How Much Does a Custom Website Cost in the UK? (2026 Pricing Guide)",
    "description": "Transparent UK website pricing for 2026. From brochure sites to enterprise platforms — what you'll actually pay, what's included, and how to avoid hidden costs.",
    "datePublished": "2026-07-19",
    "dateModified": "2026-07-19",
    "author": { "@type": "Person", "name": "Raj Naik", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/about/" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "xSoft Ltd", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/social-card.svg" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.xsoftlimited.com/blog/how-much-does-a-website-cost-uk/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How much does a basic website cost in the UK in 2026?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A basic brochure website (5-10 pages, responsive design, contact form) typically costs between £1,000 and £3,000 in the UK. This covers design, development, and initial setup but usually excludes ongoing hosting and maintenance." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Why do custom websites cost more than template-based ones?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Custom websites are built from scratch to match your exact business requirements, brand identity, and user workflows. Template sites use pre-built designs with limited customisation. Custom builds cost more because they require original design work, bespoke development, and tailored functionality that templates cannot provide." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What ongoing costs should I budget for after my website launches?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Plan for hosting (£10-100/month), domain renewal (£10-50/year), SSL certificate (often free with modern hosting), security updates, content updates, and potential SEO work. Most businesses should budget £100-500/month for maintenance depending on site complexity." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "How long does it take to build a custom website?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A brochure site takes 2-4 weeks. A business site with CMS and integrations takes 4-8 weeks. Complex web applications or e-commerce platforms take 8-16 weeks. Rush timelines are possible but typically add 20-50% to the cost." }},
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Should I hire a freelancer or an agency for my website?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Freelancers are cost-effective for simpler projects (£1-5K range) but may lack breadth of skills. Agencies offer full-service teams but charge premium rates (£5-50K+). Consultancies like xSoft offer agency-quality technical delivery with more transparent pricing and direct access to senior developers." }}
    ]
  })} />

  <section class="pt-10 pb-8">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-indigo-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Website Cost UK</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
        <div class="mb-8">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-4">
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Pricing</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">Web Development</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">UK Business</span>
            <span class="px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-xs bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20">2026 Guide</span>
          </div>
          <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-black text-white leading-tight">How Much Does a Custom Website Cost in the UK? (2026 Pricing Guide)</h1>
          <div class="mt-4 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
            <time datetime="2026-07-19">19 July 2026</time>
            <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
            <span>12 min read</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Introduction -->
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Ask five web developers what a website costs and you'll get five wildly different answers. One quotes £500, another says £50,000. Both might be right — for very different projects.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">The truth is, "how much does a website cost?" is a bit like asking "how much does a house cost?" Without knowing the size, location, specification, and finish quality, no honest answer exists. But that doesn't mean pricing should be a black box.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-8">This guide breaks down real UK website costs for 2026 — based on our experience delivering projects at xSoft Ltd and current market rates across the industry. We'll cover what drives price, what's typically included (and what isn't), and how to get an accurate quote for your specific needs.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Who This Guide Is For</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">UK business owners, startup founders, and decision-makers who need a website built professionally and want to understand what they're paying for before approaching developers or agencies.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Quick Answer -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">The Quick Answer: UK Website Costs at a Glance</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Before we go deep, here's the headline summary of what UK businesses typically pay in 2026:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
            <div>
              <p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">£1–3K</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Brochure Site</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">£3–10K</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Business Site</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">£10–30K</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Custom Platform</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">£30K+</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Enterprise</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">These ranges represent the cost of professional development — design, build, testing, and launch. They exclude ongoing costs like hosting and maintenance, which we cover separately below.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The wide ranges exist because two "business websites" can be radically different. A 10-page service site with a contact form is not the same as a 50-page site with booking systems, payment processing, and a client portal. Both are "business websites" — but the second costs three to five times more.</p>

        <!-- Factors That Affect Cost -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Factors That Affect Website Cost</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Understanding what drives price helps you make informed decisions about where to spend and where to save. Here are the ten primary factors:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">1. Number of Pages</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">More pages means more design, content, and development time. A 5-page site costs far less than a 50-page one.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">2. Design Complexity</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Template-based designs are cheaper. Bespoke designs with custom illustrations, animations, and micro-interactions cost significantly more.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">3. Functionality & Features</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Contact forms are cheap. Booking systems, payment gateways, user accounts, and dashboards add complexity and cost.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">4. Content Management System</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Static sites are cheapest. WordPress adds moderate cost. Headless CMS or custom admin panels add more.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">5. Third-Party Integrations</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Connecting to CRMs, email marketing tools, payment processors, or APIs adds development time and testing requirements.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">6. SEO Requirements</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Basic on-page SEO is standard. Technical SEO audits, structured data, content strategy, and ongoing optimisation cost extra.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">7. Responsive & Accessibility</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Mobile-responsive design is now standard. Full WCAG accessibility compliance adds testing and remediation time.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">8. Timeline & Urgency</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Rush jobs cost 20-50% more. Comfortable timelines (6-8 weeks) allow for better pricing and quality.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">9. Hosting & Infrastructure</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Shared hosting is cheap but slow. Edge-deployed platforms (Cloudflare, Vercel) offer better performance at moderate cost.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
            <p class="text-indigo-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">10. Ongoing Maintenance</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Security patches, CMS updates, content changes, and performance monitoring are recurring costs often overlooked at the quote stage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Website Types & Pricing Breakdown -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Website Types and Pricing Breakdown</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">Here's what each tier actually looks like, what's included, and who it's suitable for:</p>

        <!-- Tier 1: Brochure -->
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Brochure Website — £1,000 to £3,000</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">A digital business card. Typically 3-10 pages covering who you are, what you do, and how to get in touch. No complex functionality, no user accounts, no database.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-950/10">
          <p class="text-emerald-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Typically includes:</p>
          <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
            <li>• 3-10 responsive pages (Home, About, Services, Contact)</li>
            <li>• Mobile-friendly design (template or lightly customised)</li>
            <li>• Contact form with email notifications</li>
            <li>• Basic on-page SEO (meta titles, descriptions)</li>
            <li>• Social media links and Google Maps embed</li>
            <li>• SSL certificate and initial hosting setup</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Best for:</strong> Sole traders, new businesses establishing an online presence, trades people, local services that primarily get clients through word-of-mouth but need a professional web presence.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Timeline:</strong> 2-4 weeks from signed brief to launch.</p>

        <!-- Tier 2: Business -->
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Business Website — £3,000 to £10,000</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">A proper workhorse. Multiple pages, content management, interactive features, and designed to actively attract and convert visitors. This is where most SMEs land.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-950/10">
          <p class="text-emerald-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Typically includes:</p>
          <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
            <li>• 10-30 pages with custom design throughout</li>
            <li>• Content management system (WordPress, headless CMS, or custom)</li>
            <li>• Blog or news section with categories and search</li>
            <li>• Advanced forms (multi-step, file uploads, conditional logic)</li>
            <li>• Third-party integrations (email marketing, CRM, analytics)</li>
            <li>• Technical SEO setup (structured data, sitemap, robots.txt)</li>
            <li>• Performance optimisation (image compression, caching, CDN)</li>
            <li>• Cookie consent and GDPR compliance</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Best for:</strong> Established SMEs, professional services firms, B2B companies, organisations with regular content updates, businesses that rely on their website for lead generation.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Timeline:</strong> 4-8 weeks depending on content readiness and feedback cycles.</p>

        <!-- Tier 3: Custom Platform -->
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Custom Web Application — £10,000 to £30,000</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Beyond a "website" — this is a web-based product. User accounts, databases, real-time features, complex business logic, and custom admin panels. Think SaaS tools, client portals, marketplace platforms.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-950/10">
          <p class="text-emerald-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Typically includes:</p>
          <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
            <li>• Bespoke design system with component library</li>
            <li>• User authentication and role-based access</li>
            <li>• Database design, API development, server-side logic</li>
            <li>• Payment processing (Stripe, GoCardless, etc.)</li>
            <li>• Admin dashboard for data management</li>
            <li>• Automated testing and CI/CD pipeline</li>
            <li>• Performance monitoring and error tracking</li>
            <li>• Documentation for ongoing maintenance</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Best for:</strong> Startups building their core product, businesses replacing manual processes with software, companies needing client-facing portals, organisations with unique workflow requirements.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Timeline:</strong> 8-16 weeks for MVP. Ongoing iterations beyond that.</p>

        <!-- Tier 4: Enterprise -->
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mt-8 mb-3">Enterprise Platform — £30,000+</h3>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Large-scale systems with multiple user types, complex integrations, high-availability requirements, and enterprise security needs. Often involves legacy system migration or multi-service architectures.</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-950/10">
          <p class="text-emerald-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Typically includes:</p>
          <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
            <li>• Multi-phase discovery and requirements engineering</li>
            <li>• Microservices or service-oriented architecture</li>
            <li>• Enterprise SSO, audit logging, compliance features</li>
            <li>• Multi-region deployment and disaster recovery</li>
            <li>• Load testing and scalability engineering</li>
            <li>• Dedicated project management and regular reporting</li>
            <li>• Training, handover documentation, SLA-backed support</li>
            <li>• Ongoing development retainer for enhancements</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Best for:</strong> Funded startups post-Series A, mid-market companies, organisations replacing enterprise software, businesses processing high transaction volumes.</p>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Timeline:</strong> 3-6+ months. Typically structured in phases with regular releases.</p>

        <!-- What's Included vs Extra -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">What's Included vs What Costs Extra</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">One of the biggest sources of confusion in web quotes is scope. What one agency includes as standard, another charges extra for. Here's a general guide:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-emerald-500/30 bg-emerald-950/10">
            <p class="text-emerald-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Usually Included</p>
            <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
              <li>• Responsive design (mobile, tablet, desktop)</li>
              <li>• Basic SEO setup (meta tags, sitemap)</li>
              <li>• Contact form</li>
              <li>• SSL certificate</li>
              <li>• Browser testing (Chrome, Safari, Firefox)</li>
              <li>• Initial content upload (text and images you provide)</li>
              <li>• 1-2 rounds of design revisions</li>
              <li>• Launch deployment and DNS configuration</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/30 bg-rose-950/10">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Usually Costs Extra</p>
            <ul class="text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
              <li>• Copywriting and content creation</li>
              <li>• Professional photography or videography</li>
              <li>• Logo design and branding</li>
              <li>• Ongoing SEO and content marketing</li>
              <li>• E-commerce functionality</li>
              <li>• Multilingual support</li>
              <li>• Custom animations or interactive features</li>
              <li>• Ongoing maintenance and support packages</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Pro Tip</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Always ask for a detailed scope document before signing. A good developer will itemise exactly what's included. If the quote is a single line item — "Website build: £5,000" — ask for a breakdown. You need to know what you're comparing.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- DIY vs Freelancer vs Agency vs Consultancy -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">DIY vs Freelancer vs Agency vs Consultancy</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">Your choice of who builds the site affects both cost and outcome. Here's an honest comparison:</p>

        <!-- DIY -->
        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-600/30 bg-gray-900/30">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
            <span class="text-lg">🔨</span>
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">DIY (Wix, Squarespace, WordPress.com)</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cost:</strong> £0-500/year (subscription + domain)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Pros:</strong> Cheapest option. Full control over timeline. No external dependencies.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cons:</strong> Limited design options. Poor performance. SEO limitations. Time-intensive to learn. Looks like a template site.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400"><strong class="text-gray-300">Best for:</strong> Personal projects, hobby sites, very early-stage businesses testing an idea.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Freelancer -->
        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-600/30 bg-gray-900/30">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
            <span class="text-lg">👤</span>
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Freelance Developer</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cost:</strong> £1,000-8,000 (project-based or day rate £200-500)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Pros:</strong> More affordable than agencies. Direct communication. Flexible timelines. Often specialists in one area.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cons:</strong> Single point of failure (illness, holiday, disappears). May lack design skills if they're a developer (or vice versa). No backup team.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400"><strong class="text-gray-300">Best for:</strong> Small businesses with clear requirements who want cost-effective professional delivery.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Agency -->
        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-gray-600/30 bg-gray-900/30">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
            <span class="text-lg">🏢</span>
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Digital Agency</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cost:</strong> £5,000-100,000+ (varies enormously by agency size and reputation)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Pros:</strong> Full-service team (design, dev, SEO, content). Project management included. Process-driven. Ongoing support structures.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cons:</strong> Expensive overheads passed to clients. You may not work with senior people day-to-day. Slower decision-making. Contractual rigidity.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400"><strong class="text-gray-300">Best for:</strong> Larger businesses with significant budgets who want a managed, full-service experience.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Consultancy -->
        <div class="not-prose my-4 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-2">
            <span class="text-lg">⚡</span>
            <p class="text-white font-semibold text-sm">Technical Consultancy (like xSoft)</p>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cost:</strong> £3,000-30,000 (project-based with transparent breakdowns)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Pros:</strong> Senior developers on every project. Direct access to decision-makers. Modern tech stack. Performance-first approach. Transparent pricing.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-2"><strong class="text-gray-300">Cons:</strong> Smaller team means capacity limits. May not offer traditional creative agency services (branding, print). Less suitable for very large enterprise programmes.</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400"><strong class="text-gray-300">Best for:</strong> Businesses that value technical quality over bureaucracy. Startups wanting senior expertise without agency pricing. Companies needing modern, high-performance web platforms.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Hidden Costs -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Hidden Costs Most People Miss</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">The build cost is just the beginning. Many businesses are surprised by ongoing expenses they didn't budget for. Here's what to plan for beyond the initial development fee:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/30 bg-rose-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-rose-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">⚠️ Annual Running Costs (Typical UK Business Site)</p>
          <div class="space-y-3 mt-3">
            <div class="flex justify-between items-center border-b border-gray-700/50 pb-2">
              <span class="text-sm text-gray-300">Domain name (.co.uk or .com)</span>
              <span class="text-sm text-rose-400 font-medium">£10–50/year</span>
            </div>
