        <!-- How to Get an Accurate Quote -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">How to Get an Accurate Quote</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">If you're ready to approach developers for quotes, here's how to get the most accurate and comparable pricing:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📋 Steps to an Accurate Quote</p>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Define your goals:</span> What should the website achieve? Lead generation? Online sales? Information hub? Brand credibility? Be specific.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">List your pages:</span> Write down every page you need. Home, About, Services (one per service?), Blog, Contact, FAQ, Pricing. Count them.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Identify functionality:</span> Forms? Booking system? Payment processing? User accounts? File uploads? Map each feature to a page.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Gather inspiration:</span> Find 3-5 websites you admire. Note what you like — layout, animations, colour schemes, features. Share these with developers.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">State your budget range:</span> This isn't a negotiation weakness — it helps developers scope appropriately. "We have £5-8K" gets you a more relevant proposal than silence.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">6</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Set a timeline:</span> When do you need it live? Be realistic. "Next week" limits your options. "Within 2 months" opens up better pricing.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">7</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Ask about ongoing costs:</span> Get a clear answer on what you'll pay monthly/annually after launch. This is where surprises live.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Red Flags in Quotes</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Be wary of quotes that: have no scope document, lock you into proprietary platforms you can't leave, don't mention ongoing costs, promise "unlimited revisions" (nothing is unlimited), or are dramatically cheaper than all other quotes (usually means corners will be cut).</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-6 mt-6">
          <div class="border-b border-gray-700/50 pb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">How much does a basic website cost in the UK in 2026?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A basic brochure website (5-10 pages, responsive design, contact form) typically costs between £1,000 and £3,000 in the UK. This covers design, development, and initial setup but usually excludes ongoing hosting and maintenance. At the lower end you'll get a template-based design with minimal customisation. At the higher end, you'll get a lightly bespoke design with better typography, imagery, and on-page SEO.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-700/50 pb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">Why do custom websites cost more than template-based ones?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Custom websites are built from scratch to match your exact business requirements, brand identity, and user workflows. Template sites use pre-built designs with limited customisation. Custom builds require original design thinking, bespoke frontend development, tailored backend logic, and thorough testing. You're paying for engineering time and expertise — the same reason a bespoke suit costs more than one off the rack.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-700/50 pb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">What ongoing costs should I budget for after launch?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Plan for hosting (£10-100/month), domain renewal (£10-50/year), SSL certificate (often free with modern hosting), security updates, content updates, and potential SEO work. Most businesses should budget £100-500/month for maintenance depending on site complexity. Modern edge-deployed sites on platforms like Cloudflare can significantly reduce the hosting portion of this.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="border-b border-gray-700/50 pb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">How long does it take to build a custom website?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A brochure site takes 2-4 weeks. A business site with CMS and integrations takes 4-8 weeks. Complex web applications or e-commerce platforms take 8-16 weeks. The biggest variable is usually content readiness — if you provide copy, images, and feedback promptly, timelines compress significantly. Rush timelines are possible but typically add 20-50% to cost.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="pb-4">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">Should I hire a freelancer or an agency?</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Freelancers are cost-effective for simpler projects (£1-5K range) but carry single-point-of-failure risk. Agencies offer full-service teams but charge premium rates to cover overheads. Technical consultancies like xSoft offer a middle path — agency-quality technical delivery with transparent pricing, direct access to senior developers, and lower overheads. The right choice depends on your budget, project complexity, and how much hand-holding you need through the process.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Common Mistakes -->
        <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-indigo-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-indigo-400 pl-4">Common Mistakes When Commissioning a Website</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">Having worked with dozens of clients across different industries, we see the same mistakes repeated. Avoid these and you'll save both money and frustration:</p>

        <div class="not-prose my-6 space-y-4">
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Choosing purely on price</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">The cheapest quote usually means the developer is either inexperienced, planning to cut corners, or will hit you with change requests later. A £1,500 site that needs rebuilding in 18 months costs more than a £4,000 site that lasts five years.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Not having content ready</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">The number one cause of project delays is waiting for client content. Write your copy, gather your images, and prepare your brand assets before development begins. Or budget for copywriting as part of the project.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Ignoring mobile from the start</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Over 60% of UK web traffic is mobile. If your developer isn't designing mobile-first, you're building for the minority. Check their portfolio on your phone — if their own sites aren't responsive, yours won't be either.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Skipping the brief</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A written brief protects both parties. It defines what's being built, what's out of scope, and what "done" looks like. Without one, expect disagreements about what was included in the price.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">Treating SEO as an afterthought</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SEO needs to be baked into the architecture from day one — URL structure, page speed, structured data, heading hierarchy. Retrofitting SEO onto a poorly-built site is expensive and often futile.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-rose-500/20 bg-rose-950/5">
            <p class="text-rose-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">No plan for post-launch</p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A website isn't "done" at launch — it's just beginning. Plan for content updates, security maintenance, analytics review, and iterative improvements. The best websites evolve continuously.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

